The paper deals with data structures for representing and manipulating simplicial complexes, which are objects of interest in computational geometry, topology, and data analysis. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses compression techniques, which are relevant to cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The analysis of the data structures involves combinatorial and probabilistic arguments, which are typical of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
